<span id="freeTextContainer14705874886858718245">If you&apos;d have told me two years ago that I&apos;d read 72 Renaissance fabliaux and love them all so perfectly... well, I wouldn&apos;t have known what any of that meant, but I wouldn&apos;t have believed it even if I did!<br/>These stories are so rich in detail. Some are still funny today, others still incredibly sad. The discussions that accompany them reveal gender and class divides, some of which are still prevalent today. Whoever says these older texts aren&apos;t relevant anymore is so wrong!<br/>There&apos;s so much textual</span>
  <span id="freeText14705874886858718245" style="display:none">If you'd have told me two years ago that I'd read 72 Renaissance fabliaux and love them all so perfectly... well, I wouldn't have known what any of that meant, but I wouldn't have believed it even if I did!<br />These stories are so rich in detail. Some are still funny today, others still incredibly sad. The discussions that accompany them reveal gender and class divides, some of which are still prevalent today. Whoever says these older texts aren't relevant anymore is so wrong!<br />There's so much textual analysis to be done here, and I'm sure I can get a few essays worth out of the Heptameron before the end of this academic year, but more than anything this text is just fun to read.</span>
