    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3796586665" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3796586665" />
    <a title="David Welch" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23483638-david-welch"><img alt="David Welch" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1623363440p2/23483638.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3796586665?book_show_action=true">Jan 25, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Welch" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Welch" href="/user/show/23483638-david-welch">David Welch</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3796586665" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer840826912446903721">I can only review this book by comparing it to the two books it patterns itself after, the Decameron of Boccaccio and the Canterbury Tales of Chaucer. Like them it is a cycle of stories told by different narrators, and ranges from the bawdy to the prim and proper. It&apos;s just the French version instead of Italian or Middle English.<br/><br/>The book, reputed to be by Marguerite of Navarre (Though this has never been verified), only gets to seventy-two stories. And when compared to Decameron or Canterbury, i</span>
  <span id="freeText840826912446903721" style="display:none">I can only review this book by comparing it to the two books it patterns itself after, the Decameron of Boccaccio and the Canterbury Tales of Chaucer. Like them it is a cycle of stories told by different narrators, and ranges from the bawdy to the prim and proper. It's just the French version instead of Italian or Middle English.<br /><br />The book, reputed to be by Marguerite of Navarre (Though this has never been verified), only gets to seventy-two stories. And when compared to Decameron or Canterbury, it just doesn't measure up. The stories are of a lower narrative quality, and are usually much shorter. This isn't to say they are bad, there are a number of good ones in fact, but not nearly as many as the book's more famous predecessors. It also suffers from being extremely obsessed with relationships. Almost every story here has something to do with people in love, people cheating on each other, or people taking sexual advantage of others (To put it mildly). Decameron and Canterbury had tales like this, but they mixed it up more, with a wider variety of subjects. In Heptameron I can only remember one story that wasn't build around relationships, and it wasn't that memorable. This focus does become repetitive, and you'll pretty much run into every minor variation of relationship drama you could imagine in these tales.<br /><br />The books strengths, besides the better of its stories, are it's narrative characters and it's setting. Being a primary text of the 1500s, you really do get a good feel for the type of people that lived then. They're instantly familiar because people haven't really changed much in the last 500 years. The book also uses its narrators as full-fledged characters in their own right, having discussions after each story about the implications, and the moral lessons that can (or can't) be drawn from it. In fact I think it does that part better than Decameron or Canterbury.<br /><br />All told, it's a minor classic for a reason. There's good stuff here to read and remember, but it just doesn't rise up to top tier storytelling. Good but not great.</span>
  <a data-text-id="840826912446903721" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

