<span id="freeTextContainer16245638902938695839">I want to first start by saying I can’t believe I read and enjoyed a book written in the 1500s. I first heard of the book from another, which was Call Me By Your Name by André Aciman. After reading and watching the movie and seeing the scene where Elio’s mom reads the line from story 10, “is it better to speak, or to die”, I knew I HAD to know the rest of the story. <br/><br/>Amador was a knight, and he was in love with a young girl named Florida, but he had to hide his feelings because of her high-born p</span>
  <span id="freeText16245638902938695839" style="display:none">I want to first start by saying I can’t believe I read and enjoyed a book written in the 1500s. I first heard of the book from another, which was Call Me By Your Name by André Aciman. After reading and watching the movie and seeing the scene where Elio’s mom reads the line from story 10, “is it better to speak, or to die”, I knew I HAD to know the rest of the story. <br /><br />Amador was a knight, and he was in love with a young girl named Florida, but he had to hide his feelings because of her high-born position. As an excuse to be around her, Amador marries one of Florida’s ladies in waiting and eventually declares his love for her by using the line above. Afterwards, she confesses her feelings for him. BUT they both misunderstand each other and because of this and the “norms” way back when, once Amador is surrounded in war he decides that love is dead and he would rather stab himself than die at the hand of another and Florida spends the rest of her life in a nunnery! <br /><br />I enjoyed the book. It was a story inside of a story. I liked that it was divided by each story and day. With that being said, it was really repetitive. Marguerite de Navarre must’ve really liked a good forbidden romance!</span>
